<manpage>
    <sample url="sdk\operating_system\crt\libc\stdio\putchar">putchar</sample>
    <title> putchar, putwchar</title>
    <volume>C Run-Time Library Functions</volume>
    <routine_idx> stio_idx.htm </routine_idx>

    <description>
        <para>Writes a character to stdout. </para>
    </description>

    <syntax>
        <return_val>int</return_val>
        <func_name>putchar</func_name>
        <parameters>
            <func_param>
                <param_type>int</param_type>
                <param_name>c</param_name>
                <param_note>
                    <para>Character to be written. </para>
                </param_note>
            </func_param>
        </parameters>
    </syntax>

    <syntax>
        <return_val>wint_t</return_val>
        <func_name>putwchar</func_name>
        <parameters>
            <func_param>
                <param_type>wint_t</param_type>
                <param_name>c</param_name>
            </func_param>
        </parameters>
    </syntax>

    <return>
        <para>Each of these functions returns the character written. To indicate an error or end-of-file condition, putchar returns EOF; putwchar returns WEOF. For both routines, use ferror or feof to check for an error or end of file. </para>
    </return>

    <remarks>
        <para>The putc routine writes the character c to the output stream at the current position. For each routine, if a read error occurs, the error indicator for the stream is set. putwchar is the wide-character version of putchar. </para>
    </remarks>

    <requirements>
        <routine>
            <routine_name>putchar</routine_name>
            <headerfile>stdio.h</headerfile>
            <compatibility>ANSI, Windows 2000, Elastos 2.0</compatibility>
        </routine>
        <routine>
            <routine_name>putwchar</routine_name>
            <headerfile>stdio.h</headerfile>
            <compatibility>ANSI, Windows 2000, Elastos 2.0</compatibility>
        </routine>
    </requirements>

    <example>
<pre>
//==========================================================================
// Copyright (c) 2000-2007,  Elastos, Inc.  All Rights Reserved.
//==========================================================================

/* putchar.cpp: This program writes characters from
 * buffer to screen.
 */

#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;

int main()
{
    char  buffer[] = &quot;Testing putwchar.&quot;;
    char  *p;

    p = buffer;
    while (*p) {
        putchar(*p);
        p++;
    }
    putchar(&apos;\n&apos;);

    return 0;
}
</pre>
    </example>
<result>
Testing putwchar.
</result>



